The two relevant directives:

require-trusted-types-for 'script' — DOM XSS sinks (element.innerHTML, eval, document.write, script.src, etc.) require a TrustedHTML / TrustedScript / TrustedScriptURL value, not a string
trusted-types default — Names the policy that's allowed; we create one called default at app boot
Trusted-Types policy
if (window.trustedTypes && window.trustedTypes.createPolicy) {
  window.trustedTypes.createPolicy('default', {
    createHTML: (s) => DOMPurify.sanitize(s, { RETURN_TRUSTED_TYPE: true }),
    createScript: (s) => s,                      // We never createScript with user input
    createScriptURL: (s) => {
      const allowed = ['https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/', 'https://unpkg.com/'];
      if (!allowed.some(p => s.startsWith(p))) throw new Error(`Blocked script URL: ${s}`);
      return s;
    }
  });
}
What is and isn't a TT sink
This is the load-bearing fact: fetch() request bodies and XMLHttpRequest.send() payloads are NOT Trusted-Types sinks. The strict CSP does not block our outbound API calls or our SSE consumption — it only governs DOM injection. So Worker C's userscript-side fetch(url, {credentials:'include'}) is unaffected by claude.ai's strict CSP. From MDN — Trusted Types8: "Trusted Types covers DOM XSS sinks: Element.innerHTML, Element.outerHTML, Document.write, Range.createContextualFragment, script element src/text/textContent, eval, setTimeout/setInterval with string args, Worker/SharedWorker URL, iframe.srcdoc. Network APIs are not covered."

DOMPurify with RETURN_TRUSTED_TYPE: true integrates natively. Mermaid output (which uses innerHTML) needs to wrap its render in a TT-aware shim or we set securityLevel: 'strict'.

worker-src blob: is required for Monaco's web workers (Monaco creates inline workers via Blob URL). frame-src blob: is required for the artifact iframe with srcdoc.

