Hard rules carried forward into the build
No document.cookie reads anywhere. Cookie auth flows only through credentials: 'include' (browser-supplied) in the userscript companion, never in Worker B itself.
No real Anthropic egress from Worker B directly. All outbound goes through WORKER_C_URL or WORKER_A_URL — the operator's own infrastructure.
BLOCKED_HOSTS list (openclaude.111724.xyz, cfc.aroic.workers.dev, 111724.xyz, aroic.workers.dev) is hardcoded as a final fail-safe in the outbound URL validator; any attempt to route there throws.
Terminal Amber is mandatory. No claude.ai logos, no AnthropicSans, no left-sidebar+right-artifact layout. ASCII bracket buttons, monospace plan badges.
Mutation modes are orthogonal to auth modes. The strip/replace/prepend/append/inject_canary logic operates on the request body before dispatch; it applies equally across all four auth modes.
inject_canary defaults OFF. Operator must explicitly set WC_MODE=inject_canary and supply the canary string. Off by default in every published config.
Single operator only. No multi-tenant features; the mock signup is local-config only and Worker A's /auth/signup rejects requests when single_operator: true is set after the first registration.
This reference is the implementation contract. Each section maps to verifiable bytes; nothing here is filler. With it, Worker B becomes a 1:1 functional twin of claude.ai/chat carrying the exact API call patterns through to WORKER_C_URL, while remaining visually unmistakable as a research artifact under the Terminal Amber design system.

